  "opinion": "As a mechanic in Bologna with three children and a background that’s a mix of practical hands-on work and limited formal education beyond upper secondary, I’ve seen firsthand how stereotypes about STEM fields can affect people. Stereotype threat isn’t just a theory—it’s real, and it hits hard when someone feels their identity or group is being judged negatively in a field they’re trying to enter. For me, it’s about the anxiety that creeps in when you’re told, ‘You’re not cut out for this,’ especially if you’re from a group historically underrepresented in STEM. I’ve worked with many young people who feel discouraged because they’ve been told they’re not ‘the type’ to do engineering or physics. This isn’t just about individual confidence—it’s a systemic issue that needs addressing. But how do we do it without overwhelming those who are already stressed? I think the key is creating environments where people feel safe to fail and where their worth isn’t tied to their performance in a single subject. For example, in my shop, I’ve noticed that when we talk about fixing cars, it’s not about being ‘smart’ in a traditional sense—it’s about problem-solving and patience. Maybe we should start by normalizing the idea that everyone learns at their own pace and that mistakes are part of the process. Addressing stereotype threat isn’t about changing the system overnight—it’s about small, consistent efforts to build trust and reduce the fear of being labeled. For those of us who are anxious, this kind of support can make a huge difference. It’s not just about STEM—it’s about creating spaces where everyone feels they belong.",
